id: aic-project
type: project
version: 1.0
owner: architect

project:
  name: AIC — AI Compiler
  description: >
    A CLI tool that compiles .intent files to any target
    language using a configured AI provider. Implements
    the Intent-Oriented Architecture (IOA) methodology.

  capabilities:
    - Parse and validate .intent files across four levels
    - Resolve inheritance chain from project to component level
    - Scaffold new components with pre-linked boilerplate intent files
    - Compile intent to any target language and version via AI
    - Delta-based recompilation — surgical updates not full regeneration
    - Bidirectional sync — code changes reflected back to intent
    - Lockfile management — track intent versions per component
    - Status tracking — STALE, DRIFT, VIOLATION per component
    - Audit — validate code against declared guidelines
    - AI provider abstraction — Claude, Gemini, Ollama, Copilot

  prerequisites:
    - python >= 3.10
    - git >= 2.0
    - configured AI provider (Claude / Gemini / Ollama)

  commands:
    - aic init      ← project setup and language detection
    - aic create    ← component scaffolding with linked boilerplate
    - aic compile   ← intent to code compilation
    - aic sync      ← bidirectional code to intent sync
    - aic status    ← STALE, DRIFT, VIOLATION tracking
    - aic audit     ← guideline compliance check
    - aic validate  ← intent file quality check
    - aic transpile ← full project migration to new language target

architecture:
  principles:
    - Single responsibility per module — one module does one thing
    - No hardcoded values anywhere — all config via aic.config.json
    - All AI provider interaction goes through the provider adapter layer only
    - File I/O is always explicit — no implicit reads or writes
    - Every operation must be reversible or clearly documented as not
    - Fail loudly — no silent failures, all errors surface with clear messages
    - Deterministic phases must remain deterministic — no AI in Phase 1, 2, or 4
    - Git must be present and initialised — AIC will not run outside a git repo

  security:
    - No API keys in code, logs, or error messages ever
    - No execution of generated code — AIC generates, never runs
    - All file writes are scoped to project directory only
    - No network calls except to configured AI provider endpoint

  quality:
    - Every function has a single clear purpose
    - No function longer than 30 lines
    - No nested conditionals deeper than 3 levels
    - All errors handled explicitly — no bare except clauses
    - No dead code committed

  patterns:
    - Adapter pattern for all AI provider integrations
    - Strategy pattern for compilation targets
    - Observer pattern for status tracking